[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering Groovy compatibility**\n\nI need to figure out if I can make the test Java-compatible. There's a possibility of including .java files under src/test/groovy, but the rule states these should be Groovy test files. Existing Groovy tests seem to fail in native due to GroovySystem, and I'm wondering if previous reports were after the JVM. \n\nIt might be worth looking into using `@CompileStatic`, which might help eliminate GroovyObject issues. I need to check if I can compile those classes without running the tests just yet.\n\n**Evaluating Groovy class implementation**\n\nI'm thinking about whether Groovy classes always implement GroovyObject unless they're annotated with @POJO. I wonder if there's also @CompileStatic involved here, but I don't think Groovy 4 has a @POJO option. Could a Java file under src/test/groovy be accepted? It seems like the top-level test classes must be public, so the rule about dedicated Groovy test files probably leans towards .groovy. \n\nHowever, is there a way to avoid failures in native? Also, it looks like invoking ObjectConverter.class$ requires private access. Maybe I could use MethodHandles.privateLookupIn for reflection-like behavior here.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_08a39db4d756753f016a117ab1349c8192ae7c3525f0817705\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqEXq98pL3QfZcovqhiPuMwmJeRR9t04KNnZTEmQBmrQxexMB8Zg5vX3LDX0VwygEmsHs5Kb7_YbTMmIiCqE8rGH9GcAQweQ3cpXRbTzeyzFV-zdPYUZbxdF-E22gifhiGU-dYOjE1SpRMBUfaFuEl09ZKF2xGXXBFfzdvYqSzsmuHykAi6JH-h1OUEfi4cnX3MJcO2WMINjVy-Tp5vnyxptj4Wir-XYrOCuBS8UkkWUhtmvKcE33e_OUEGecRg1b2av1Lra7yNGna0WgrrUKFBr4G50VZgDngBScaieC89JUj4tmnG5ulvQ09rzlm1iGLFjDtc7O-sXloUUxfHb122_SVXRWPQ0lAPKfQHhWx-ecWRB5y-zKmOdhgU2Zl7x1inUw8jj03ui4dZn-i7XWJT9KkO7eMo7DFdDvZePGSgn50MZNqUNebgtXNRhbE9FFZBxcY8Z7B58BIj7ENBRKhbEYQChdVmvSPoEcsg8Cm80EkKL7pTx39rnxhIZ1ZSQPSvGuhIAeNUOXHOe5wODTJvj1Qhedu